				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\mathfrak {S}(X),\delta )$$\end{document} considered in Sect. 6 has some special topological properties. Note that a similar combinatorial technique was used by Ardila and Klivans (2006) to understand the topology of spaces of (unranked) equidistant trees.

Finally, Theorem 6.1 implies that methods for performing a variety of statistical computations (e.g. Fréchet mean and variance (Bacák 2014; Miller et al. 2015), an analogue of partial principal component analysis (Nye et al. 2017) and confidence sets (Willis 2019)) can be applied (or extended) to the metric space \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
